  "style": "",
  "texts": [
    "This means that: \\\\[ \\\\cos \\\\theta = \\\\cos (\\\\theta + 360k) \\\\] for any integer \\\\(k\\\\).",
    "\", \"Given \\\\(\\\\cos 568^\\\\circ\\\\), we need to reduce this angle to an equivalent angle within the first cycle of \\\\(0\\\\) to \\\\(360^\\\\circ\\\\).",
    "We do this by subtracting multiples of \\\\(360^\\\\circ\\\\) until we get an angle within this range: \\\\[ 568^\\\\circ -360^\\\\circ = 208^\\\\circ \\\\] So, \\\\(\\\\cos 568^\\\\circ = \\\\cos 208^\\\\circ\\\\).",
    "\", \"However, we want to find \\\\(n\\\\) such that \\\\(0 \\\\leq n \\\\leq 180\\\\).",
    "Since cosine is also symmetric about \\\\(180^\\\\circ\\\\), we know that: \\\\[ \\\\cos \\\\theta = \\\\cos (180^\\\\circ -\\\\theta) \\\\] Therefore, \\\\(\\\\cos 208^\\\\circ = \\\\cos (180^\\\\circ -208^\\\\circ)\\\\), which simplifies to: \\\\[ \\\\cos 208^\\\\circ = \\\\cos (-28^\\\\circ) \\\\]\", \"The cosine function is also even, meaning it is symmetric about the y-axis: \\\\[ \\\\cos (-\\\\theta) = \\\\cos \\\\theta \\\\] Thus, \\\\[ \\\\cos (-28^\\\\circ) = \\\\cos 28^\\\\circ \\\\]\", \"So, \\\\(n = 28^\\\\circ\\\\)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": []
}